    <exploration>
        <title>Angles at the Centre and Circumference</title>
        <interactive xml:id="interactive-angle-at-circumference" platform="jsxgraph" width="90%" aspect="1:1" source="jsxgraph/angle-at-circumference.js">
            <slate xml:id="jsxgraph-angle-at-circumference" surface="jsxboard" aspect="1:1"/>
            <instructions>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Try moving <m>P</m>. What do you notice about the angles <m>\angle AOB</m> and <m>\angle APB</m>?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Try changing the radius of the circle with the slider. What happens to the angles?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Do the angles change if you move <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                What happens if <m>P</m> moves past <m>A</m> so that it lies on the <term>minor arc</term> <m>AB</m>? What new formula might we need?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </instructions>
        </interactive>
    </exploration>
    <insight>
        <p>
            <strong>Making Sense of the Geometry: Real-World Visualizations</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
            To understand how these circle theorems work, let us connect them to everyday visual ideas:
        </p>
        
        <p>
            <strong>1. The Slingshot Rule (Angle at the Centre)</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
            Imagine holding a giant circular slingshot anchored at two fixed perimeter pegs, <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> (your arc). 
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    If you pull the slingshot pocket back to the exact center point <m>O</m>, the elastic forms a wide, open angle (<m>\angle AOB</m>).
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    If you stretch it all the way back to any point <m>P</m> on the far circular boundary, the elastic becomes tighter and narrower. 
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            Because the boundary point <m>P</m> is much farther away from your pegs than the center, the angle at the circumference is always exactly <strong>half</strong> the size of the angle at the center. Alternatively:
        </p>
        <me>\text{Angle at the Centre} = 2 \times \text{Angle at the Circumference}</me>
        <me>\angle AOB = 2 \times \angle APB</me>

        <p>
            <strong>2. The Theater Stage Rule (Angles in the Same Segment)</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
            Imagine points <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> represent the left and right sides of a stage in a circular amphitheater. Points <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>, and <m>R</m> are seats at different locations in the balcony.
        </p>
        <p>
            Even though the seats are in different spots (one on the left, one in the middle, and one on the right), every single spectator looks at the exact same width of the stage. As long as you stay on that same curved balcony boundary, your "viewing angle" stays constant!
        </p>
        <me>\angle APB = \angle AQB = \angle ARB</me>

        <p>
            <strong>3. The Right-Angle Split (Angle in a Semicircle)</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
            This is a special case of the Slingshot Rule. If you place your anchors directly opposite each other, the line connecting them is the diameter (<m>RT</m>). 
        </p>
        <p>
            The central angle is now a perfectly flat straight line running through the center <m>O</m>, which measures exactly <m>180^\circ</m>. Since the angle at the edge must be half of the angle at the center, picking any boundary point <m>S</m> and connecting it to the diameter ends will always create a perfect right angle:
        </p>
        <me>\angle RST = \frac{180^\circ}{2} = 90^\circ</me>
    </insight>
    <insight>
        <p>
            <strong>Mastering Circle Geometry</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
            . To build spatial reasoning and solve complex geometric problems, a  learner needs to master three key skills:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <strong>Identifying Subtending Arcs:</strong> Always trace back from the vertices of the angles to the circle's boundary. Identifying which specific arc (or chord) is "holding up" the angles is the secret to choosing the correct theorem.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <strong>Spotting the Radii:</strong> Many circle geometry problems involve hidden isosceles triangles. Remember that any line drawn from the center <m>O</m> to the boundary is a radius (<m>r</m>). Since all radii are equal, triangles formed by two radii and a chord always have two equal base angles.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <strong>Recognizing Segments:</strong> A chord splits a circle into a major segment (the larger area) and a minor segment (the smaller area). Remember that the <em>Angles in the Same Segment</em> theorem only applies when the vertices of the circumference angles lie within the exact same segment.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </insight>

